<section xml:id="lesson-03">
  <title>Lesson 3 - Transformations of Functions</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>Describe sequences of transformations applied to a function.</li>
      <li>Apply transformations to a given graph.</li>
      <li>Graph transformed functions starting from a parent function.</li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="l3-transform-expressions">
    <title>Transformations of a Given Function</title>

    <p>
      Describe the sequence of transformations given by each expression,
      then apply the transformations to the function shown in the graph below.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="l3-base-function">
      <caption>Graph of a base function used to apply and visualize transformations.</caption>
      <image source="../figures/functrans-review.png">
        <description><p>Graph of a base function used to apply and visualize transformations.</p></description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <exercises>
      <exercise xml:id="l3-ex1">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li><m>f(x)+2</m></li>
            <li><m>f(x+2)</m></li>
            <li><m>f(-x)-2</m></li>
            <li><m>2f(x+2)</m></li>
            <li><m>\frac{1}{2}f(2x)-2</m></li>
            <li><m>2f\left(\frac{1}{2}x\right)</m></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            For each expression, identify vertical shifts, horizontal shifts,
            reflections, and stretches or compressions, then apply them to the
            given graph.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="l3-transform-equations">
    <title>Transformations of Parent Functions</title>

    <p>
      Describe the sequence of transformations described by each equation,
      then graph the function by applying those transformations to the
      appropriate parent function.
    </p>

    <exercises>
      <exercise xml:id="l3-ex2">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li><m>f(x)=\frac{4}{x-1}+2</m></li>
            <li><m>f(x)=\sqrt[3]{x-1}+3</m></li>
            <li><m>f(x)=-\frac{1}{2}\lvert -x\rvert</m></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Begin with the appropriate parent function, then apply horizontal
            shifts, vertical shifts, reflections, and scalings in the correct order.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>
  </subsection>

</section>